# Git - Staging to production flow (DevOps spine)

Reference: [autogit/gitupdate.md](autogit/gitupdate.md) (when it exists in the project).

Agent Kit treats this flow as the agents' **operational memory**: plan -> handoff -> staging -> prod -> memory. Without a structured promote step, handoffs go stale and the agent loses track of what has already shipped.

## Commands

| Command | Slash | Destination (in this repo) | Use |
|---------|-------|------------------------------|-----|
| `git staging` | `/git-staging` | `origin/staging` | Bring local changes to staging (working branch, commit, MR, merge). |
| `git prod` | `/git-prod` | `origin/main` | Promote approved staging to production. |

Legacy projects may name the pre-prod branch `homologacao`, `develop`, etc.; the **two-step pattern** stays the same and the canonical name is `staging`. See the decision in `.cursor/memory/decisions/` (branch naming).

## Critical rule

- **NEVER** commit directly to `main`, nor push to `origin/main` without going through `origin/staging`.
- When committing on the user's behalf: use **`git staging`** (do not commit to `main`).
- Promotion to production only via **`git prod`**, after approval in staging.

## Flow + memory

```
Plan (.cursor/plans/) -> work -> /handoff
    -> git staging -> origin/staging
    -> (approval) -> git prod -> origin/main
    -> memory-loop WRITE if it applies
```

After staging or prod: update `.cursor/HANDOFF.md`. If the promote closed an incident or a tradeoff decision, record it in `.cursor/memory/` (memory-loop rule).

## Validations

- BLOCKED: commit to `main`, push directly to `origin/main`, merging a local branch directly into `main`.
- ALLOWED: commits on a working branch; push to `staging`; promotion `staging` -> `main` via `git prod`.

## Staging-first and enforcement

The "never commit to `main`" rule only works if the checkout is not on `main` while working.

- **Never work on `main`.** Commits happen on a working branch or on `staging`. `git prod` leaves the checkout on `main`; when done, switch back with `git checkout staging`.
- **Hook guards.** Install the `pre-commit` and `pre-push` hooks from [git-hooks/](../../git-hooks/) that abort a commit/push directly to `main`/`master`. This makes the block enforced, not just a convention.
- **Audit the `main` line.** `git log --first-parent --no-merges main` should only list the root commit. Any other non-merge commit on that line was born directly on `main`.
- **Prune legacy branches.** A pre-prod branch (`homologacao`, `develop`) already migrated to `staging` should be deleted, locally and on remotes, so it does not confuse the flow.

## Conventional Commits

Use prefixes: `feat:`, `fix:`, `docs:`, `refactor:`, `chore:`, `test:`, `style:`, `perf:`.

## When the user says

- **`git staging`** - Full routine in [autogit/gitupdate.md](autogit/gitupdate.md) ("Prompt: git staging" section): validation, CHANGELOG (`[Unreleased]`), checkout staging, pull, working branch, commit, push, MR, merge, cleanup; then HANDOFF.
- **`git prod`** - Routine in [autogit/gitupdate.md](autogit/gitupdate.md) ("Prompt: git prod" section): validation, close the release in the CHANGELOG, summary, **explicit confirmation**, merge to main, push; then HANDOFF (+ public sync in this monorepo if applicable).

## Quick troubleshooting

- "Direct commits to main are blocked" -> use `git staging`.
- `staging` branch does not exist -> `git checkout -b staging` and `git push -u origin staging`.
- Legacy repo with `homologacao` -> same command; migrate to `staging` when possible (see gitupdate.md, Naming section).
